                    <h1>Javascript Arrays</h1>
                    <div dir="ltr" style="text-align: left;" trbidi="on">
<br />
<b><i><u><span style="color: #674ea7;">Javascript Arrays</span></u></i></b><br />
<br />
An Array is an enumerated list of variables.<br />
The index can be referenced by a variable, allowing for easy looping through the data structure.<br />
<br />
for(i=0; i&lt;6; i++) {<br />
&nbsp; &nbsp;document.write(x[i]+'&lt;br&gt;);<br />
}<br />
<br />
Which will output the following…<br />
<br />
0<br />
1<br />
2<br />
3<br />
4<br />
5<br />
<br />
<b><i><u><span style="color: #674ea7;">Creating A New Array</span></u></i></b><br />
var myArray = [];<br />
<br />
<b><i><u><span style="color: #674ea7;">Initializing An Array</span></u></i></b><br />
with pre-defined data…<br />
<br />
var myArray = ['January', 'February', 'March'];<br />
document.write('0&gt;'+myArray[0]+'&lt;BR&gt;'); &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;// Will output: 0&gt;January<br />
document.write('1&gt;'+myArray[1]+'&lt;BR&gt;'); &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;// Will output: 1&gt;February<br />
document.write('2&gt;'+myArray[2]+'&lt;BR&gt;'); &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;// Will output: 2&gt;March<br />
<br />
<b><i><u><span style="color: #674ea7;">Storing Data In An Array</span></u></i></b><br />
An array can store anything you can assign to a variable: booleans, numbers, strings,<br />
functions, objects, other Arrays, even regular expressions…<br />
<br />
var myArray = [ 3, 'hello!', function() {return 5}, {'color':'blue', 'budget':25}, /[ell]/i ];<br />
document.write('0&gt;'+myArray[0]+'&lt;BR&gt;'); &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;// Will output: 0&gt;3<br />
document.write('1&gt;'+myArray[1]+'&lt;BR&gt;'); &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;// Will output: 1&gt;hello!<br />
document.write('2&gt;'+myArray[2]()+'&lt;BR&gt;'); &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;// Will output: 2&gt;5<br />
document.write('3&gt;'+myArray[3].color+'&lt;BR&gt;'); &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;// Will output: 3&gt;blue<br />
document.write('3&gt;'+myArray[3].budget+'&lt;BR&gt;'); &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; // Will output: 3&gt;25<br />
document.write('4&gt;'+myArray[4].test(myArray[1])+'&lt;BR&gt;'); // Will output: 4&gt;true<br />
<br />
&nbsp;<b><i><u><span style="color: #674ea7;">Arrays Passed By Reference</span></u></i></b><br />
Arrays are passed to functions by reference, or as a pointer to the original.<br />
This means anything you do to the Array inside the function affects the original.<br />
<br />
var myArray = [ 'zero', 'one', 'two', 'three', 'four', 'five' ];<br />
<br />
document.write(myArray[1]); // Will output: one<br />
<br />
function passedByReference(refArray)<br />
&nbsp;{<br />
&nbsp; &nbsp;refArray[1] = 'changed';<br />
}<br />
<br />
passedByReference(myArray);<br />
<br />
document.write(myArray[1]); // Will output: changed<br />
<br />
<br />
<b><i><u><span style="color: #674ea7;">Arrays &nbsp;Assigned By Reference</span></u></i></b><br />
Assigning an Array to a new variable creates a pointer to the original Array<br />
<br />
var myArray = [ 'zero', 'one', 'two', 'three', 'four', 'five' ];<br />
var newArray= myArray;<br />
<br />
newArray[1] = 'changed';<br />
<br />
document.write(myArray[1]); // Will output: changed<br />
<br />
<br />
<b><i><u><span style="color: #674ea7;">Passing Arrays As Values</span></u></i></b><br />
To pass an Array by value instead of by reference, use the Array.slice() method.<br />
<br />
var myArray = [ 'zero', 'one', 'two', 'three', 'four', 'five' ];<br />
var newArray= myArray.slice();<br />
<br />
newArray[1] = 'changed';<br />
<br />
document.write(myArray[1]); // Will output: one<br />
<br />
function passedByReference(refArray) {<br />
&nbsp; &nbsp;refArray[1] = 'changed';<br />
}<br />
<br />
passedByReference(myArray.slice());<br />
document.write(myArray[1]); // Will output: one<br />
<br />
<span style="color: #674ea7;"><b><i><u>Array Methods&nbsp;</u></i></b></span><br />
Some of the array methods<br />
concat()<br />
join()<br />
pop()<br />
push()<br />
<br />
Reference for detailed array methods explained:<br />
<a href="http://www.w3schools.com/jsref/jsref_obj_array.asp">http://www.w3schools.com</a><br />
<a href="http://www.tizag.com/javascriptT/javascriptarray.php">http://www.tizag.com/javascriptT/javascriptarray.php</a><br />
<a href="http://www.javascriptkit.com/jsref/arrays.shtml">http://www.javascriptkit.com/jsref/arrays.shtml</a><br />
<br />
<b><i><u><span style="color: #674ea7;">Howto Easily Add Items To An Array</span></u></i></b><br />
<br />
There are three ways to easily add items to an array. First you can use the Array.length property.<br />
Since Arrays start with index 0, then Array.length is always equal to the first empty index at the end of the Array.<br />
<br />
var myArray = [];<br />
myArray[0] = 'January';<br />
myArray[1] = 'February';<br />
<br />
document.write(myArray.length); &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;// Will output: 2<br />
<br />
myArray[myArray.length] = 'March'; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; // Adds Item to end of Array<br />
<br />
document.write(myArray.length); &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;// Will output: 3<br />
<br />
document.write('0&gt;'+myArray[0]+'&lt;BR&gt;'); &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;// Will output: 0&gt;January<br />
document.write('1&gt;'+myArray[1]+'&lt;BR&gt;'); &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;// Will output: 1&gt;February<br />
document.write('2&gt;'+myArray[2]+'&lt;BR&gt;'); &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;// Will output: 2&gt;March<br />
<br />
You can add the .push() method of the Array. This will add the requested items to the end of the Array.<br />
<br />
var myArray = [];<br />
myArray[0] = 'January';<br />
myArray[1] = 'February';<br />
<br />
myArray.push('March'); &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; // Adds Item to end of Array<br />
<br />
document.write('0&gt;'+myArray[0]+'&lt;BR&gt;'); &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;// Will output: 0&gt;January<br />
document.write('1&gt;'+myArray[1]+'&lt;BR&gt;'); &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;// Will output: 1&gt;February<br />
document.write('2&gt;'+myArray[2]+'&lt;BR&gt;'); &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;// Will output: 2&gt;March<br />
<br />
You can use the .unshift() method to insert an item at the BEGINNING of the array<br />
<br />
<br />
var myArray = [];<br />
myArray[0] = 'February';<br />
myArray[1] = 'March';<br />
<br />
myArray.unshift('January'); &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; // Adds Item to beginning of Array<br />
<br />
document.write('0&gt;'+myArray[0]+'&lt;BR&gt;'); &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;// Will output: 0&gt;January<br />
document.write('1&gt;'+myArray[1]+'&lt;BR&gt;'); &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;// Will output: 1&gt;February<br />
document.write('2&gt;'+myArray[2]+'&lt;BR&gt;'); &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;// Will output: 2&gt;March<br />
<br />
